\description{
\code{meep()} produces honest, cross-fitted (out-of-fold) nuisance estimates
for use in Double Machine Learning (DML) and causal-forest workflows.
For an outcome \code{y}, an optional \code{treatment}, and covariates \code{X}, it
cross-fits an ensemble of the package's base learners -- by default
\code{\link[=ares]{ares()}} (MARS), \code{\link[=krls]{krls()}} (Kernel Regularized Least Squares), \code{\link[=ols]{ols()}},
and \code{\link[=logreg]{logreg()}}, with \code{\link[=bgam]{bgam()}} (P-spline boosting) available opt-in --
and returns the
out-of-fold predictions \eqn{\hat E[Y\mid X]} and (when \code{treatment} is
supplied) \eqn{\hat E[D\mid X]}, plus the residuals \eqn{Y-\hat Y} and
\eqn{D-\hat D}.
}
\details{
\code{meep()} does \strong{not} estimate a treatment effect. The honest OOF
predictions are meant to be handed to a downstream DML estimator or to
\code{grf::causal_forest()} (see Examples). Because each column of the OOF
prediction matrix already comes from a model that never saw the row it
predicts, the stacking ensemble (\code{ensemble = "stack"}) can fit
non-negative least squares directly on that matrix without a second
layer of nesting -- leakage is already purged column-wise.
}
\section{Family auto-detection}{

When \code{family} is \code{NULL}, a binary \code{y} (exactly two distinct values)
triggers \code{ares(family = "binomial")} and \code{krls(loss = "logistic")};
otherwise the gaussian path is used. The same logic applies to
\code{treatment_family}: a binary treatment is modelled as a propensity
score via logistic regression, a continuous treatment via gaussian
regression. A treatment with three or more distinct values is rejected
(multi-valued / continuous-treatment IRM is out of scope).

The family also governs which default learners are fitted for each
nuisance. \code{ares} and \code{krls} are family-agnostic and always apply.
\code{ols} is fitted only for gaussian (continuous) nuisances; \code{logreg} and
\code{plda} are classification learners fitted only for binomial (binary)
nuisances. Because the Y-model and the D-model can differ in family,
applicability is resolved \emph{per nuisance}: a gaussian outcome with a
binary treatment fits \code{ols} for \code{outcome}/\code{mu0}/\code{mu1} and
\code{logreg}/\code{plda} for \code{treatment}. A learner that does not apply to a
nuisance is simply skipped -- its OOF column stays all-\code{NA} and it is
\emph{not} recorded as a fold failure.
}

\section{Tuning (\code{tune})}{

\itemize{
\item \code{"once"} (default) -- autotune each learner on the full data, freeze
the resulting hyperparameters, and refit those frozen settings within
every fold. Standard DML practice: fit honesty (cross-fitting) is what
protects inference; freezing hyperparameters is a deliberate, second-
order compromise.
\item \code{"per_fold"} -- autotune independently inside every fold. Purist
option; slower.
\item \code{"none"} -- the fast path. Call \code{\link[=ares]{ares()}} and \code{\link[=krls]{krls()}} with their own
default arguments (plus anything passed via \code{ares_args} / \code{krls_args}).
No autotune is invoked at all.
}
}

\section{Graceful degradation}{

If a learner errors on a fold (for example, a constant nuisance in a
fold subset), its column for that fold becomes \code{NA}, the ensemble
weights are renormalized over the surviving learners on a per-row basis,
and the event is logged in \verb{$fold_failures}. If \emph{every} learner fails a
fold, \code{meep()} stops.
}

\section{DoubleML recipe}{

To use these nuisances with the \pkg{DoubleML} package, pass
\code{y_hat_oof} / \code{d_hat_oof} as \code{external_predictions} and reuse
\code{fit$folds} as the sample split so the cross-fitting partition matches.
}

